##Saving Wuhan: Documenting the toughest three weeks since the siege | the cover of CAIJING

I-CAIJING

CAIJING magazine official Wechat. A megalopolis of more than 10 million people went into shock after a sudden outbreak of the disease, and then struggled out of the chaos without hope

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Financial Cover. Creative Design / Lai Lap

By Liu Yiqin and Xinna, special correspondent for Caijing from Wuhan, Wang Xiao from Caijing, Fang Gongyiliu, Li Shiyun, Yu Qin, Wang Lina, Wang Jingyi, Chen Liang, Li Siyang, and Li Yinxi contributed by Li Xingjun

Editors | mark, Song Wei, Zhu Tao, Xie Lirong, Shi Zhiliang

The empty streets, the masked faces, the gated communities, the intercity traffic, the invisible and seemingly omnipresent dangers... for Chinese over 30, the end of winter and the beginning of spring in 2020, it's like 17 years ago.

From winter to spring to mid-summer in 2003, SARS (Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome) , also known as Atypical pneumonia, which originated in Guangdong Province, attacked China from south to north. Hong Kong, Guangdong, Beijing, Shanxi and Taiwan were designated as epidemic areas by the World Health Organization (WHO) .

According to the WHO, 5,327 people in mainland China were infected with SARS, and 349 died. In Hong Kong, China, 1,775 people were infected and 300 died. In Taiwan, China, 665 people were infected and 180 died.

SARS quickly spread to 26 countries outside China, including Singapore and Canada, where 8,422 people were infected and 919 died.

In January 2004, China launched the Information System for monitoring infectious diseases and public health emergencies (the direct reporting system on the Internet) , which covers health institutions throughout the country. Pneumonia of unknown causes is one of the key points for its monitoring and reporting. According to regulations, hospitals at all levels should report infectious cases as soon as possible in the system, and the China Center for Disease Control and Prevention in Beijing can see the report information at the same time.

The SARS like virus may appear at any time, Takatomi, a member of the The National Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference and the Chinese Academy of Sciences, said in an interview with Jinyang.com on March 4,2019, but the National Infectious Disease Surveillance Network is well established, and China will not have "SARS-like incidents. ".

Nine months later, COVID-19 pneumonia (NCP) was on the rise. In early December 2019, the city of Wuhan, the epicenter of the outbreak, was forced to close down more than a month after the first case of the disease occurred in Wuhan. As of 2400 hours on February 14,2020, a total of 66,492 people had been diagnosed with new pneumonia and 1,523 died, according to the National Health Commission. In Hubei Province, 54,406 people were diagnosed and 1,457 died.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
As of February 14, a city in Wuhan, a total of 37,914 confirmed cases, 1123 deaths.

"All that a man can gain from the plague and the gamble of life is knowledge and memory, " read the 1957 Nobel Prize in Literature winner Albert Camus's masterpiece, the plague

The collective memory of Wuhan in early 2020 will be the beginning of China's next decade.

An unprecedented siege

At 2:00 am on January 23, the Wuhan Epidemic Prevention and Control Headquarters announced that from 10:00 am on the same day, the city's bus, subway, ferry, long-distance passenger transport operations were suspended; the airport and railway stations were temporarily closed from the Han corridor. Recovery time will be announced later. This "closure of the city" was interpreted by the public as a "lock-in" .

An unprecedented battle between humans and viruses has begun.

This is not an ordinary epidemic, nor is it a repeat of the SARS epidemic in mainland China 17 years ago, but the first time in human history that a megacity of tens of millions of people has been cordoned off in peacetime. What followed was a reallocation of health care resources, a near standstill in urban life, and months of temporary economic stagnation.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Workers inspect the west side of the South China Seafood Wholesale Market in Wuhan on Jan. 11,2020. Figure / Fachen

Wuhan, the Industrial and commercial center of Central China, is at the center of the epidemic, with the Yangtze River crossing the city. Wuhan is also the largest land, water and air transport hub in China and a shipping center in the middle reaches of the Yangtze River. Its high-speed rail network covers more than half of China and is the only city in central China with direct links to five continents.

Some foreign media refer to Wuhan as the "Chicago of China" because it also has a declining steel industry and College Station, China's largest city, where about 1m people attend school. Wuhan is also home to a number of large car factories that make cars for global brands such as GM, Nissan and Honda.

The new coronavirus outbreak in the "thoroughfare of nine provinces, " Wuhan, and the Spring Festival brings a large-scale population migration, which has become a common nightmare for many epidemiologist and millions of people.

The local government explained, "the closure of the city can effectively cut off the route of transmission of the virus, resolutely curb the spread of the epidemic, and ensure the safety and health of the people. "

Chinese and foreign medical experts were shocked by the scale of the blockade and wondered whether the local government had overreacted. Even at the height of the SARS epidemic 17 years ago, the city chose not to impose such a strong quarantine, opting instead to concentrate patients in a makeshift hospital in the Beijing suburb of Xiaotangshan.

It is a reflection of the disease's unpredictability, its magnitude, and its dread -- a disease that governments are willing to pay an unprecedented price for.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On January 17,2020, medical staff sent patients to Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital. Cinematography fearless

As of January 23, the day the city was declared closed, 571 new cases of pneumonia had been confirmed in Wuhan, which did not look so bad. But just three weeks later, on February 14,37,914 cases had been confirmed in Wuhan!

Wuhan "closed" message as a warning bell, so that the original knowledge of the epidemic little or do not think that the Chinese people across the country have put on a mask, seriously.

On the day of Wuhan's "City closure" , millions of people went in the direction they most believed in, in the face of the few options available.

Many people fled Wuhan overnight. Liu Lin, a resident of Jingzhou, hit a top speed of 160 kilometers per hour on the highway without a break. Soon, the high-speed train out of the city is full, leaving late has been difficult to move.

At 8:30 am on January 23, only two ticket counters were open at the Hankou Railway Station, and some Wuhan citizens directly dragged their suitcases to the ticket hall of the Railway Station to buy tickets and go out of the city. According to incomplete statistics from Caijing, at least 251 trains were sent from Wuhan on January 23 between 00 and 10:00, traveling north to Harbin, south to Shenzhen, east to Shanghai and West to Chengdu. At least one hundred thousand people were scattered across the country by train.

At 10:00 a.m. , the "closing of the city" began. Armed Police stood in a line, surrounding the Hankou Railway Station, allowing only passengers to leave the station and not to enter. One person who boarded the last train said he saw many people crying when they failed to get tickets.

Airlines have also been up all night, cancelling most flights involving Wuhan, but the last flight left Wuhan at 1255 on January 24 for reasons including "soft landing" and connecting flights. Immediately, Wuhan Tianhe Airport, which handles nearly 30 million passengers a year, closed its departure channel.

At 2 pm, a number of expressways in Hubei Province began to close, some "loopholes" have been closed: Gongjialing, Xiaojunshan, Hannan, Beihu, Hanayama, Baiquan, Qinglong, West Lake Station entrance closed; The Beijing–Hong Kong–Macau Expressway, West Wuhan, North Wuhan, Caidian District and Yong'an toll gates were closed; other highway crossings out of Wuhan were also closed.

On January 26, the Mayor of Wuhan, Zhou Xianwang, announced that there were more than 11 million permanent residents, more than 9.9 million registered residents and nearly 5 million migrant workers in the city. As of that day, more than 5 million people had left and more than 9 million remained in the city.

Some fled, while others backtracked to Wuhan.

Zhang Xu, a nurse at a local hospital in Wuhan, had returned home to spend the New Year with her family. On January 23, the 20-year-old girl rushed back to Wuhan overnight. The driver took her to the service station before the wuhan-to-city expressway. She walked a long way in the dark, carrying her luggage and turned over several roadblocks. After entering the city, Zhang Xu waited by the side of the road for several hours.

Zhang Xu was stopped on her way into the city and asked what she was doing there? "I'm a nurse, and I have to go back, " she answered.

The sense of responsibility for life goes beyond the fear of the unknown. For many ordinary Wuhan residents, staying or going has never been an issue, because Wuhan remains their home even if the epidemic is severe.

In the early morning of January 23, Wang drove from Wuhan to Hengyang on business. On the way, he received a text message from Wuhan that he was about to close the city. He immediately turned back. Wang runs a perlite factory in Xinyang, 200 km from Wuhan, with annual revenues of more than 100m Yuan.

Wang Chen came back because he couldn't let go of his family. He also wanted to do something about the epidemic, and later joined Shouqi's team of volunteer drivers in Wuhan to provide transportation services for those in need, including transporting supplies and medical personnel.

Back in Wuhan, Wang found that most supermarkets had run out of vegetables and 84 disinfectant; cars lined up for gas; and the fever clinic was overcrowded and hard to get a bed.

CAIJING reporter called all the designated hospitals in Wuhan on the day of the "closure of the city, " including the first three hospitals: Hankou Hospital, Red Cross hospital and Seventh Hospital, and the second group of four hospitals: Fourth Hospital, West side, Ninth Hospital, Wuchang Hospital, Fifth Hospital, only the Red Cross hospital has beds, other designated hospitals have their own hundreds of beds are full.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The isolation ward of Caidian District People's Hospital in Wuhan, February 6,2020. Photograph: Chen Zhuo

The serious shortage of medical protective materials was a common problem in Wuhan hospitals at that time. When the third hospital became a designated hospital, it did not have enough protective materials in reserve. When Caijing contacted the hospital by telephone on the afternoon of January 23, doctors had only a small number of masks, medical caps and almost no protective clothing and goggles.

The Wuhan University of Science and Technology said doctors could only use surgical masks, not protective clothing. N95 masks only in fever clinics and quarantines. They're waiting for supplies. A nurse at the Hubei Provincial People's Hospital told Caijing that eye clinics, which had nothing to do with the outbreak, had been set up as isolation zones filled with infected staff.

But the hospital did not expect that a bed is hard to find, the problem of shortage of materials lasted longer.

On the afternoon of January 23, a light rain began to fall in Wuhan. Citizen Zhou Xue went downstairs to buy medicine and found that the pharmacy had closed. But the chess and card room below his house was still bustling, with people pushing cards boldly and almost no one wearing masks.

At that time, Zhou Xue was still thinking about when to report the chess and card room downstairs, and when to go to work after the Spring Festival. But the next three weeks were a long time for him, as if her father was hospitalized with a new coronavirus that killed her.

After Wuhan "closed the city" , other cities in Hubei "closed the city" one after another. As of the evening of January 28, all cities in Hubei, except the Shennongjia, had suspended external transport, including trains and civil aviation, as well as urban public transport to varying degrees.

At first, many residents thought it was just an interrupted Spring Festival. It wasn't until after the city was closed that the outbreak and the shutdown of transport reminded citizens that disasters are fair and relevant to everyone, whether they are doctors, patients, drivers or just another member of the city.

Subsequent events have shown that the blockade of Wuhan has largely prevented the virus from spreading nationally and globally. But for Wuhan, after an unprecedented three weeks, it is already overwhelmed. The effect of isolation on the functioning of society is too great to be sustained in the long term, but the unknowable and uncertain nature of the new coronavirus makes it necessary to persist.

As of Feb. 14, three weeks after the city was shut down, the government had poured money, personnel and supplies into the city, but the health care system was still struggling to keep up with the rising number of patients, despite the blockade of the airport, high-speed rail, state, provincial and village roads, but there are people who have found ways to escape the blockade and reunite with their families, and despite efforts to collect masks, protective clothing and goggles, there are still a large number of health care workers who lack basic protective equipment; Although public opinion and experts are stressing the highly infectious nature of the epidemic, there are still countless brave people who have volunteered to go to the front line to help fight the epidemic.

People who are desperate for help and looking out for others

More than nine million people remained in Wuhan after the city was closed. Data from Feb. 14 showed that Wuhan had 37,914 confirmed cases, with 1,123 deaths, or about one confirmed case for every 240 people.

After the city was sealed off, Wuhan became an empty city. Caijing noted that there were few cars on the city's main roads and no people in the most bustling central attractions, with only 120 ambulances shuttling between homes and hospitals. In this big, empty city, people are hoarding food and medicine and quarantining in their homes.

Ran, who lives in a village in Liuzhijie, Huangpi District District, Wuhan, has not had fresh vegetables for two weeks. She eats preserved fish and preserved meat every day. In order to eat vegetables, she called communities, streets and even the National Development and Reform Commission, and finally turned to the media for help.

The vegetable supply point is on the street, and Ms. Ran said that many residents were afraid to take an emergency bus because they had heard that the bus had been carrying patients with fever. Couriers couldn't get in, let alone a city-wide delivery. Ms. Ran wanted the vegetable supply to sink, but the street replied, "there's no way. ".

Mr. Shen runs a beef soup shop a few kilometers from the south-central hospital. He was originally from Xinyang, Henan Province, and had planned to return to his hometown on New Year's Eve, but the city was closed, so he and his family stayed behind. A few days ago, he reopened the take-out shop, because take-out platform suddenly"do not smoke".

Each can "earn a few dollars" , but it takes a lot of risk. Mr. Shen installed two doors and placed takeout food in boxes outside, wearing a face mask and disposable gloves the entire time. The system also automatically crossed out all orders from the hospital.

Ordinary people have such a hard time. "closed city" , the guests did not, the original dozens of orders fell to only a few. And the money's all over the place. A few hundred dollars a day in rent, a loan owed, 200,000 yuan to open the cost of the shop, a family of food and drink... he just paid tens of thousands of yuan rent or borrowed from elsewhere.

He had been doing business in Jiangsu, introduced by a friend, only a few months ago to Wuhan, did not expect to encounter the epidemic. Under the economic pressure, Mr. Shen did not care to be afraid, he only hoped to go home as soon as possible, "never again dare to set foot in Hubei (do business) . ".

If the shortage of supplies only lowers people's living standards, the relative lack of medical resources across the city in the face of a rapidly spreading epidemic could be fatal.

Liu Bai's mother-in-law is a cancer patient. She was supposed to go to Wuhan People's Hospital for treatment on the seventh day of the Lunar New Year (January 31) , but it has been postponed indefinitely. The limited medical resources are almost entirely focused on new coronary pneumonia patients. And Her mother-in-law the same patients there are many, some of the body inserted a syringe needle, have to be temporarily removed.

Liu Bai said, mother-in-law hypothyroidism (hypothyroidism) medicine also did not have, the doctor said there is no way, can only find their own. She went to a lot of pharmacies and was lucky to find two boxes.

She bought the first masks on Dec. 30,2019, when cases were rare and officials said they could be prevented and controlled, but on Jan. 20,2020, academician Zhong Nanshan came to Wuhan to investigate and publicly stressed that "human-to-human transmission is guaranteed. " Before she understood the severity of the outbreak.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On January 20,2020, Zhong Nanshan called the COVID-19"absolutely 'human to human' . " Tuxinhua

Cell will be issued daily temperature checklist, the situation in the afternoon, Liu Bai will go to ask why fever patients are still isolated at home. Ms. Ran asked "CAIJING" reporter, "is not that 98.6% of the household investigation, how we have not been investigated? "

"The doctor clearly said that the father is a COVID-19, but because there is no test box can not be confirmed, " Sun Chen told Caijing in late January. Sun Chen's father had a cough and fever years ago, and the family didn't take it to heart. On the second day of the Lunar New Year (January 25) , "closed city" a few days, the father coughed up blood. Sun Chen hurriedly sent his father to Huazhong University of Science and Technology Hospital for examination, lung CT results showed infection.

"I didn't think it would fall on my own family, " said Sun Chen, whose parents had never visited the Wuhan Seafood Market and only bought vegetables at a nearby market. The family did not wear masks until the day of the siege.

Sun Chen, whose father is 70 and whose mother is 66, both have basic illnesses such as high blood pressure and diabetes and can only be isolated at home. "I must send my father to a hospital bed, " Sun Chen said.

What does a bed mean? Unable to find a bed, Kai Lee, who lives in Hanyang, blinked and watched his father snort and die all night. His father was a military transfer officer and a pillar of the family. After the tragic death of his father, the funeral home car took more than 10 hours to arrive, they are also very busy, a pull several times.

The grandmother of Chen Li, a railway worker in Wuhan, sat for three days in the outpatient hall of the Hankou Hospital because she did not have a hospital bed. She died of exhaustion.

These patients had not been diagnosed before their death, so they were not counted as "confirmed deaths" .

By early February, CAIJING reporters had interviewed more than a dozen families in Wuhan, most of whom had contracted the disease, helping critically ill elderly people and pregnant women move from hospital to hospital, seeking beds for their families in the line of life and death.

According to"CAIJING"reporter understands, general only two kinds of path can be admitted to hospital. First, by the Community Queue, patients first to the community to hand in lung CT, blood routine reports, the community report to the street, and then according to the priorities of the new docking hospital beds, patients need to take the hospital admission sheet; Second, to have a designated hospital nucleic acid test paper queue, 48 hours to get the results, confirmed can not be rejected by the hospital.

But until Wuhan urgently takes steps to centralize care and liberalize diagnostic criteria, neither path will be easy. Each path could be a Tsuruoka Station, and both could be life and death.

On February 1, a doctor at Wuhan's Fifth Hospital told Caijing that the designated hospital had a large number of cases waiting in line with hospital admission forms, but could not be admitted because of the shortage of beds.

Then there is the false negative problem of the kit. Another doctor at a designated hospital told Caijing that the positive rate of nucleic acid test in his hospital was only 45% , and patients had to be tested several times before they could be diagnosed.

Under the epidemic situation, the admission of special population has also become a problem. A family member of a pregnant woman who lives near a paper workshop kindergarten in Jiangxia District, Wuhan, told Caijing that the pregnant woman at home was eight months pregnant and the latest diagnosis showed severe infection of both lungs.

But the fixed-point fever clinic does not accept pregnant women, the clinic also does not have the fetal heart monitor, the district mother and child and the province mother and child do not receive the fever patient. A few days after the family tweeted for help, they got the attention of the community and the district government on January 31. They were driven to and from several hospitals by community vehicles, and finally were admitted to the East Hospital of People's Hospital of Wuhan University on the morning of February 1.

KIMIAKI's father had been on regular dialysis at China Resources Wugang Hospital. But after his father was diagnosed with NCP, the hospital rejected Kimiaki's request for treatment. "patients with NCP can only be treated at designated hospitals. ". But in designated hospitals such as Wuhan's Third Hospital and Wuchang Hospital, Kimiaki was told "dialysis rooms are closed" .

"I haven't found a place to do dialysis yet, " Kimiaki told Caijing on Feb. 4, adding that the deadline was the next day. The countdown to kidney dialysis is even more brutal than the new coronary pneumonia, and without timely dialysis, the patient's massive water retention (swelling caused by interstitial fluid) remains in the body and can be life-threatening. Within 72 hours, Kimiaki was in more than 20 hospitals, barely sleeping.

All this took a turn for the better in early February.

On February 5, the Hubei Provincial Health and Health Commission issued a public notice on designated hospitals for the treatment of pneumonia among special population groups in the province, setting out the designated hospitals for pregnant women, children and dialysis patients after suspected or confirmed cases of COVID-19 pneumonia. Among them, dialysis patients can choose Wuhan Third Hospital Guanggu District, Wuhan Po Oi Hospital Gutian District, Hankou Hospital, Wuchang Hospital.

At 11:00 am that day, through the Coordination of Wuhan City Health Commission, his father finally admitted to the Ninth Hospital of Wuhan Intensive Care Unit. At 4 p.m. , paramedics pushed a dialysis machine into the ward. "Daddy's finally GonNa be okay, " Kimiaki said.

In an epidemic, it's hard to say which family is luckier. Sometimes, the habit of despair is more deadly than despair. "finance" reporter in the interview patient family, heard many times "the community does not care, the hospital does not accept, save us, we have no way! "

Since February 1, Wuhan Health Commission and other government departments have taken a series of urgent actions, from the opening of beds in Huoshenshan and Leishenshan hospitals to the establishment of a shelter hospital, the bed problem has been alleviated. Previously blocked nucleic acid tests have been gradually liberalized. More importantly, the implementation of "four categories of personnel" centralized admission order 10.

"Four categories of personnel" are: confirmed patients, suspected patients, can not definitively rule out the possibility of new pneumonia fever patients, confirmed patients with close contacts. Among them, seriously diagnosed patients and suspected patients must be admitted to hospital treatment, and can not be admitted to other hospitals or hotels, such as the need for centralized isolation treatment. The regulations also add centralized isolation measures for patients with fever and close contacts.

These new initiatives are widely recognized as powerful measures to cut off sources of infection and prevent cross-infection.

At 5:00 p.m. on February 2, The stone in Luo Yi's heart finally fell to the ground. His brother, who had been seriously ill for several days and had no access to medical care, was informed by the community health station that he could move into the central isolation point that night.

But at 8 p.m. , Ms. Luo received a call from the driver of the Community Health Station: "your brother needs to leave the hotel under quarantine. " He was stunned. The brother was then sent home with a fever of more than 39 degrees Celsius, which the community health station said was too high to receive without a doctor and testing equipment.

Those who arrive at the quarantine point need to take their temperature first, and those who are critically ill may be discouraged from entering. A nurse explained that because the hotel is only observation quarantine point, can not injection can not take medicine, "there is no rescue measures, if patients feel that the situation is very dangerous, really advised not to live. ". For the isolation point did not arrange the corresponding isolation measures, Luo Yi felt some regret.

Quarantines are expected by people with suspected symptoms, where nucleic acid tests can be done and family infections can be avoided. However, the settlement of the isolation point determines whether it can receive the suspected patients safely and completely, and also decides whether it can control the epidemic source in time.

In the three weeks since the "closure of the city" , Liu Mei has experienced the undiagnosed death of her mother-in-law, the inability of her eldest brother, her second brother and her husband to be hospitalized for infection, and the inability of her father to buy medicine for lung cancer, "I was the only one in my family who wasn't infected, but I was about to collapse, " she told Caijing

All of Liu's patients were treated around Feb. 7, with the opening of several new shelter hospital isolation points and thousands of new beds in designated hospitals in Wuhan. Now, she has become a volunteer community building, active inspection of the district garbage disposal problems.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
February 5,2020 at 9:00 pm, the first batch of new coronavirus mild pneumonia patients have arrived in Wuhan International Convention and Exhibition Center Shelter Hospital. Photograph: Chen Zhuo

Wuhan residents have been through a lot in the past three weeks. Some people to the beginning of the epidemic only vague awareness, never thought he would personally affected the whole family, or even loved ones died. In the long and severe fight against the epidemic, they fought for help, but also to help.

A hospital in the midst of an epidemic

All the hospitals have become the most crowded places in Wuhan. Chinese Academy of Engineering Academician Li Lanjuan said on Feb. 3 that early detection, early diagnosis, early isolation and early treatment are needed to combat the epidemic of NCP, but they are not yet available in Wuhan.

A large number of health care workers were infected due to incomplete knowledge of the route of transmission of the virus and lack of protective materials. Not only do they have to treat patients, but they have to protect themselves, and hospitals in Wuhan are out of order.

As of February 11,1,716 medical workers had contracted new pneumonia, and six died in the line of duty, according to the National Health Commission. "during SARS, there were not so many medical staff infected, " Peng Zhiyong, director of the Department of Critical Care Medicine at Zhongnan Hospital of Wuhan University, told Caijing.

From January 6 to 17, the "two sessions" were held in Wuhan and Hubei provinces. In addition to the 41 confirmed cases reported by Wuhan Health Commission on January 11, there were no new cases of coronary pneumonia reported by Wuhan Health Commission during the two sessions, adding that "no clear evidence of human-to-human transmission has been found" .

At this time has been infected by health care workers. A colleague of Li Wenliang, an ophthalmologist at Wuhan Central Hospital, told Caijing that after Li first alerted people to protect themselves on the wechat group on Dec. 30,2019, they rushed to buy a box of N95 masks at their own expense, but "can not buy the next day" , the hospital protection material preparation is limited, can not catch up with the diagnosis and treatment of fever patient's daily consumption.

Around January 12, Li Wenliang, as the first group of infected medical staff in the Central Hospital, was admitted to the ward. Li Wenliang, an ophthalmologist, was diagnosed with the infection in early January. Before he resumed his post, he had been "admonished" by Wuhan police for warning of the outbreak without authorization.

Huang Chaolin, deputy director of Wuhan's Jinyintan Hospital, told Caijing that health care workers in early infectious disease departments may have done a better job of protecting patients from infection, but in the departments of non-infectious diseases, some non-febrile patients may also have NCP, "which may lead to partial infection due to a lack of awareness of the virus among early medical staff. ".

Around January 10, a patient with abdominal discomfort was admitted to Zhongnan Hospital. Peng said the abdominal patient was the first to cause the infection, which he infected more than a dozen health care workers, including a doctor who passed the virus on to his family.

A 120-year-old nurse on board said she had operated on a patient with cerebral hemorrhage in the surgical anesthesiology department. The patient later admitted to having a fever for a week, and none of the six staff members were able to defend themselves during the operation.

On the evening of January 20, academician Zhong Nanshan, head of the National Health Commission's high-level Expert Group, said that "there must be human-to-human transmission" , which redefined the severity of the epidemic. In response to the "problem of cross-infection and spread of diseases due to disorderly medical treatment" of fever patients, the "7 + 7" model was established in Wuhan on January 22, namely in the vicinity of seven large hospitals in the urban area, select 7 level-ii public hospitals as designated hospitals for fever clinics, specializing in the treatment of fever patients.

It was on this day that Dr. Li Peng joined the fever clinic at one of the designated hospitals. He told Caijing that when he was notified, the list of hospitals had already been released to the public, "with almost no preparation time in between. ". That day, a large number of patients rushed into the hospital to transfer patients, but also to do ward renovation work, in a hurry.

Patients queued for more than six hours throughout the day. Many patients in bad mood, some crying, some arguing, some swearing.

At this time the entire Wuhan present situation is, the initial infected patient incubation period has already passed, the new coronary pneumonia massive outbreak, they panic to flood into each hospital, but Wuhan's medical resources have been extremely strained. Inadequate isolation conditions, lack of kits and beds, poor access to volunteer assistance, inpatient care for large numbers of patients, and unprecedented difficulties for hospitals and doctors.

Tian Lu, a doctor at Wuhan Central Hospital, told Caijing that fever, suspected patients and medical staff were wandering around outside the quarantine zone, while patients who could not be treated were sitting in the hallways. The pollution zone was getting bigger and bigger.

Zheng Junhua, deputy director of the Shanghai First People's hospital, recalled to the reporter from Caijing that after he led the first shanghai-hubei medical team into Jinyintan hospital on January 27, the first thing he said to the local doctor was, "it wasn't easy for you after a month. "

He and his team then spent nearly a week working out a detailed infection control plan. Under the plan, hospitals would have to have three zones and two passageways, with clean zones, contaminated zones and buffer zones, and different passageways for staff and patients. "In my 13 years as dean, I have never used such high-level sensory control protection measures, " Zheng said.

Li Peng said he was not informed of the procedure until Jan. 29, when he asked the department to screen the patient, report it to the hospital, and then report it to the district. Only three to five patients a day are tested in each department.

The number of beds and test kits could not keep pace with the spread of the disease.

A woman told him that her husband had been infected and wondered if he would survive the night. Li Peng looked at the CT scan of her lungs, told her there was an 80% chance it was new pneumonia, that it was serious, and gave her a hospital bill. Li Peng told her there were no beds available and she had to sign up.

"She had a breakdown. I don't know where the patient went, " Li Peng said.

"There are a lot of posts on the Internet saying that there are a lot of highly suspicious but untreatable patients in Wuhan, but from the perspective of the medical staff, we really tried our best. " In fact, for Li Peng and many medical staff, it's hard to protect yourself because medical equipment is so tight.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A surgical anesthesiologist falls asleep after surgery at a hospital in Wuhan, Jan. 27,2020.

As of January 29, there were seven suspected infected staff members in Li Peng's department, which has 10 doctors and about 20 nurses. If we extend it to the entire hospital, as of January 27,61 health care workers were suspected of being infected. They all had fevers and lung CT problems. "normally we would have to quarantine the whole hospital, but these are extraordinary times and we are so short of staff. "

Li Peng worked the night shift on January 29. Before entering the room, he saw that the prescribed mask was not up to standard, but he did not have time to hesitate. The shift cycle is four hours because masks and protective clothing have to be changed every four hours. "If I go in a minute late, it increases the risk to the people inside, " said Li Peng, who could only put it on immediately.

A member of the volunteer team "Yo! " said January 27-30 was the peak period for medical supplies in Wuhan. The main problems encountered by volunteers were high standards of medical supplies and difficult access to them; hospitals that did not accept open funding and were found to be at risk of being processed; and logistics policies that changed every day, the shipping point blew up, but the Hubei end logistics couldn't keep up.

The whole country system under the test of epidemic situation

The number of beds is increasing, but the number of patients needing treatment is increasing even more.

During an outbreak, all febrile patients have to go through the community as the first step in reporting it. Patients can not go to designated hospitals for examination by themselves. They need to get a referral form from a community hospital first.

On February 2, the Wuhan Epidemic Prevention and Control Headquarters requested that all districts must complete the centralized treatment and isolation of the existing "four categories of personnel" by 12 noon, and that the additional personnel should be "cleared by the end of the day. ". That afternoon, a community worker in Hongshan District said they had not received any notice of the "four categories" and could not do so even if asked.

"If we really want to concentrate on treatment and isolation, with so many residents and so much demand, who can meet it? Where can there be so many places for isolation? " He asked Caijing.

The layers of pressure are carried down to the base.

Every day during the outbreak, the community worker said, she received various instructions from her superiors, but very few were practical, such as sending masks to residents. "How can we send masks if we don't have them? "? It also requires that when delivering supplies to a suspected quarantined patient, the recipient must sign for them, "how can we sign if we all avoid contact? "?

One of the biggest challenges for community workers is the constant flow of forms and reports. "We have to fill out at least eight forms to solve a problem, and every day is different. If anything happens, we are asked to take photos and take a group photo immediately, " the official said, work that could have been done in half an hour often took more than an hour.

CAIJING reporter in his community service center to see, calling to send a car to the hospital fever patients continued, and fever patients directly rushed to the community service center for medical treatment. Big Government, Strong Society

In the complex and sustained process of fighting against the epidemic, the local government departments and various social institutions have also experienced a process from confusion and intermingling to gradual division of Labor and cooperation.

The Wuhan Charitable Foundation is a dedicated foundation dedicated to education and children's relief. On January 22, the day before the city closure in Wuhan, the charity foundation launched a charity convoy with more than 10,000 car owners, whose tasks include transporting medical staff to and from work, transporting hospital supplies and returning medical staff to and from the Han medical station.

But from January 30, non-public vehicles must have a pass to get on the road. On January 29, caring drivers in the Wechat Group asked the Charity Fund to help apply for passes, the foundation secretary-general Zhang Xiaoyan thought twice, issued a notice to drivers to stop picking up and dropping off. From January 22 until January 29, the convoy ran for seven days.

Zhang later told CAIJING that she couldn't get a pass in the first place, and that it was more realistic that the outbreak was concentrated in Florida for safety reasons.

The pass is coordinated by the Wuhan Epidemic Prevention and Control Headquarters, and some units are eligible to issue it, such as the Red Cross, the Charity Federation and other official organizations, Zhang said, some ride-hailing or taxi companies can also apply for a pass through their corporate credentials. Her Fund, which is run by the Wuhan Charity Federation, is a non-governmental organisation, but it is neither licensed nor eligible.

On January 25, the capacity of private professional teams such as professional online ride-hailing platforms and logistics companies was fully opened. Didi gathered more than 1,500 drivers to serve the community and medical personnel, and the first car-hailing service provided 502 drivers, cao Cao travel, Dongfeng travel and other travel platforms have set up emergency support teams in Wuhan, a total of more than 6000 vehicles.

This professional team of love from the Wuhan Epidemic Prevention and Control Headquarters to the Social Sector Emergency Collection, Zhang Xiaoyan admitted that compared to private car owners, professional team more orderly, risk control, owner safety, comprehensive effect is better.

For 7 days, Zhang Xiaoyan has been in a state of anxiety. Car Owners shuttle medical staff to and from work, the protection depends on their own, in the protection of lack of materials at the time, the foundation can only do, in the group constantly remind them "not too many times to pick up. ".

The safety protection of the volunteer taxi drivers is more systematic. Before and after each order, a series of protective procedures must be completed, including spraying disinfectant, ventilation, taking the temperature of passengers, and routine disinfection before passengers board the bus. The whole routine should be repeated three or four times a day.

With the help of the power of Internet platform, the connection efficiency of online car-hailing is also higher. They rushed out a special program for about 8,000 health care workers, embedded in the APP background, through which health care workers can call a car, eliminating the manual matching process.

When disasters cause markets and governments to fail, volunteers often fill in the gaps. Jin Jinping, director of the Center for non-profit law at Peking University, said that because of its flexibility, closeness to individuals, and timely detection and filling of blind spots, voluntary services have demonstrated functions that are difficult to replace.

Volunteer Travel Services in Wuhan during the city closure period were divided into two stages: first, after the "pause button" was pressed on Wuhan road traffic on January 23, individuals and social groups actively participated in the event and sent help in time of snow; Second, after the epidemic entered the outbreak period, professional travel companies to the main team of volunteers, led by the government, enterprises to ensure the basic transport capacity of Wuhan.

But in Wuhan and the outside world more closely linked to the material donation, as the transfer hub of donated materials, Hubei and Wuhan Red Cross weak deployment capacity has aroused widespread doubt and even anger.

The obstruction of medical materials occurred almost at the same time as the "city closure" in Wuhan. Even during the period of SARS, there was no shortage of medical materials, such as masks, protective clothing and goggles, so that doctors and nurses had to fight the virus hand-to-hand, resulting in heavy casualties. This is especially true until early February.

At the same time, donated materials but in Wuhan Red Cross Society (hereinafter referred to as "Wuhan Red Society") rented Temporary Warehouse Wuhan International Expo Center (hereinafter referred to as "National Expo") piled up like a mountain. January 28, "finance and Economics" reporters in the National Bo see, a large number of foreign aid materials stranded, Red Cross staff manual record single, falsely claimed, can not receive the phenomenon is very serious.

On January 29, a number of first-line hospitals in Wuhan issued an appeal via social media: Protective Materials are not in an emergency, but "completely gone" ! The goods and materials stored in the Red Cross warehouse are either donated to the Red Cross or not. Wuhan Union Hospital staff went to Guobo with a full set of documents to collect the targeted donations, but only to return empty handed. Meanwhile, Concorde's doctors and nurses go to war in simple protective suits fashioned from medical waste bags.

A witness at the scene told Caijing that on January 29, a van from the hospital rushed into a warehouse in Guobo and loaded 38 boxes of masks to be pulled away because of delays in obtaining approval. But unlike the Red Cross, which spread like wildfire outside, the Red Cross field personnel did their best to contact the headquarters for clearance before the goods were looted from the Concord Hospital by lorries.

Wuhan Red Cross staff repeatedly told the media that the Red Cross function is to receive, no power, only according to the instructions of the Health Commission, "We do not assume the assignment of tasks. "

People familiar with the situation told CAIJING that the distribution of materials is under the control of the Wuhan Epidemic Prevention and Control Command, but the process of distributing the materials and the principle of giving them to whom and not to whom are unclear, and that's what's happening to the distribution people. On the issue of distribution of materials, the Hubei Provincial Epidemic Prevention and Control Command sent a message to the Wuhan Epidemic Prevention and Control Command Center, requesting that "materials must be distributed within two hours" , but this request has not been implemented.

In the early days, the site commander of the Guobo warehouse was Meng Wukang, Secretary of the Leading Party Group of the Wuhan Bureau of Statistics, and the Deputy Commander of the Wuhan Bureau of Statistics, including Xia Guohua and others. Various departments are responsible for receiving and dispatching the donated materials: The Wuhan Bureau of Statistics coordinates the on-site work, and the Wuhan Bureau of Logistics is responsible for coordinating the transshipment of donated materials, wuhan Health Committee and Wuhan Red Committee of the People's Republic of China shall be responsible for the liaison of receiving donated materials, information management of entering and leaving the storehouse, drawing up the distribution list of materials, and coordinating the materials leaving the storehouse.

An internal document of the Wuhan Municipal Party Committee points out that too many intermediate links are an important cause of material obstruction. From applying to the headquarters to reaching the hospital for treatment, one needs to go through the stages of the registration and storage of the Red Cross Society, the preliminary distribution plan of the Health Commission, the examination and filing of the municipal headquarters, the inspection of materials by the quality supervision department, and the logistics and delivery of the Red Cross organizations, the whole process takes about two days.

This is in stark contrast to the effectiveness of donors. From January 25 to January 30, Shanghai Fosun group purchased 14 tons of medical supplies from the world, including more than 330,000 medical masks and more than 270,000 medical protective clothing. It took the company just four days and two hours from the start of the procurement on New Year's Eve on January 24 to the arrival of supplies in Wuhan in the early hours of January 29.

On February 1, the Wuhan Epidemic Prevention and Control Headquarters assigned Jiuzhoutong Pharmaceutical Group, one of the largest private enterprises in Hubei Province, to help the 600998.Sh  deal with the distribution of materials, four medical logistics professionals from Kyushu Tong, together with the Wuhan Red Cross, Wuhan Health Commission and the Wuhan Market Supervision and Administration Bureau Staff, Command Warehouse Staff, 24-hour shift.

On the afternoon of February 2, Kyushu Tong officially took over the Wuhan Red Cross material distribution work, the involvement of the Museum Materials Site Organization led by the head of the huake Alumni Association.

The reporter from CAIJING learned that after Kyushu took over, the flow of goods entering and leaving the warehouse was changed. After goods entering the warehouse, Kyushu checked the delivery list, classified the goods entering the warehouse, and immediately provided a detailed list of goods in stock, wuhan Health Commission after receiving the list of Kyushu Tong company inventory, within 2 hours to give the distribution plan, Kyushu Tong according to the plan after sorting, delivered to the full-time departments.

A National Museum on-site staff told the "finance and economics" reporter, the process can be materials from the past two days to a few hours out of storage time.

Kyushu took over and still has no distribution rights, with the key change being that the Wuhan Municipal Health and Health Commission reduced the time it takes to draw up a distribution plan to two hours after receiving the list.

On February 4, the Supervisory Committee of the Wuhan Commission for Discipline Inspection announced that Xia Guohua had been removed from his post as a member of the party group and Deputy Director of the Wuhan Bureau of Statistics, and that he had been given a serious inner-party warning and a major demerit for being an administrative clerk, municipal Bureau of Statistics Secretary of the Leading Party Group, Bureau Chief Meng Wukang and Wuhan Municipal Government Office Deputy Director Huang Zhitong admonished talk.

On the same day, the Commission for Discipline Inspection and supervision of Hubei Province also made a public announcement: Because in the work of receiving and distributing donations during the epidemic prevention and control period, there were such dereliction of duty and responsibility problems as not taking responsibility, violating the "three-fold-one-big" regulation, and making mistakes in information disclosure, three officials of the Hubei Provincial Red Cross were held accountable. Zhang Qin Province Red Cross party members, full-time vice-president, and to give its party a serious warning, major demerit points to the party, provincial Red Cross Party members Chen Bo serious warning, major demerit points to the Party; Party Group Secretary of the provincial Red Cross, Executive Vice President Gao Qin shall be given a warning within the party.

The reply shows that, first, the Red Cross is indeed unprofessional in dealing with the efficiency of material distribution; second, the Red Cross is completely unfair to be blamed for the early material barrier. The key to turning things around is that, in addition to Kyushu's expertise, government departments have come under pressure to become much more efficient.

Wang Zhenyao, director of the Beijing Normal University, who previously served as director of the Disaster Relief Department and the Department of Social Welfare and Charity Promotion at the Ministry of Civil Affairs, is closely following the donation and distribution of materials in the fight against the epidemic, during the Wenchuan County earthquake and SARS, he was involved in the dispatch of materials.

According to Wang Zhenyao, similar to solving the travel demand, solving the medical material demand also went through three stages: in the initial stage, the materials donated by the people met the emergency demand; in the intermediate stage, the private forces cooperated with the government; and in the third stage, government forces gradually took the lead, and private donations became an important reserve force.

Regarding the donation and dispatch of social materials for this epidemic, Wang Zhenyao believes that the list system of medical materials support can be established by relying on scientific and technological means such as big data. The requirements for medical supplies are detailed and presented dynamically in relation to the number of patients, with a particular need to indicate the number of items that need to be coordinated at the national level. Enterprises, public interest groups and individuals, under the leadership of the government to form a synergy, open and transparent. In this way, the government ensures basic supplies, private charities and hospitals dock with emergency donations, and hospitals have flexible funding and can activate purchases.

In the light of this lesson, governments and charities can do more to enliven civil society. For example, targeted donation should respect the donor's wishes, but in the initial intended donation contact, donors can be coordinated and guided to donate to the hospital, rather than goods arrived after the coordination.

Unlike the big disasters of SARS 17 years ago and the Wenchuan County earthquake 12 years ago, China's communications, Internet, big data and artificial intelligence technologies have become quite advanced by 2020. But a number of people from the technology industry interviewed by Caijing pointed out that in the early days of the outbreak, in addition to the big data on the movement of people across the country provided daily by the three major telecommunications operators to the relevant government departments, more Chinese tech companies such as Ali, tencent, jd.com, Didi, Meituan, and SF have not been deployed in time.

After a brief lag, new technologies began to be used.

In the neighboring province of Henan, the provincial capital, Zhengzhou, found Alibaba Cloud as soon as the outbreak broke out in Wuhan and set up a data center.

The data center generates a focus list that needs to be implemented at the grassroots, district, street, and community levels. If the old way, critical period, the government functions will usually use Wechat, U Disk and other means to transfer. Their disadvantages are obvious: first, they use wechat to transmit, users'data information is likely to be leaked; second, they use USB sticks to transmit too slowly.

Alibaba Cloud developed a touch platoon system, which is a lightweight development program, online fast, list import, grass roots in the mobile phone can be used to touch platoon administrator account access, solve the problem.

A big data architect told Caijing that to deal with large-scale disasters, the government needs to set up an emergency big data scheduling system, such as big data command platform, emergency logistics transportation platform, emergency material support platform. In order to improve the command efficiency of epidemic response, it is necessary to achieve efficient collection of key data, precise delivery of emergency materials and smooth operation of urban emergency traffic.

At the end of January 2020, Ma Zhaoyuan's team in the future laboratory of Tsinghua University used artificial intelligence (AI) system to establish a national epidemic spread forecasting model. CAIJING reporter learned that Shenzhen Nanshan District government has used this set of models to plan the pace of resumption of work in the district.

On the morning of February 16, a batch of vegetables donated to the hospital arrived, a total of 300,000 Jin. He was responsible for docking. "I've never seen so much food, " Wang said. But he was more looking forward to the moment when Wuhan was unsealed and the day when the epidemic truly passed.

Although looking forward to the early resumption of work, but the first car ride-hailing driver Cai Shifu does not believe that February 20 will lift the "closed city, " "The epidemic is still so serious, how can we get the end of February and the beginning of March. " The first car "closed city" to provide voluntary travel services, Cai Shifu has been a volunteer driver. The company by the full-time Rental Business (equivalent to charter) to the drivers settlement fees, this business usually 400 yuan a day, 800 yuan a day epidemic period.

On January 29, the Hubei provincial government announced that all kinds of enterprises in the province would resume work no earlier than 24:00 on February 13, and all kinds of schools would be postponed to start school. The specific start time would be determined according to the situation of epidemic prevention and control.

On Feb. 15, there were no signs of work resuming in the provincial capital, Wuhan. A civil servant working in the Civil Defense Department is strongly opposed to the recent resumption of work. "I'm walking into a trap by not going to work, " she told Caijing.

Sooner or later, the commute would go on, the siege would end and, as the book ends, the gate would open and people would be born again, happy to be together again. But at such a terrible price, we should not be exactly the same.

(at the request of the interviewee, Liu Lin, Zhang Xu, Zhou Xue, Liu Bai, Sun Chen, Luo Yi, Liu Mei, Li Peng and Wang Fan were given pseudonyms)
